Rating: 3
Made a similar dish with pesto stuffing, worked very well. Advice for the person whose chops turned out dry: (1) brine the pork chops first: immerse them in a solution of water, salt, sugar, and whatever herbs or seasonings you like for a few hours. (Ratios of water to salt and water to sugar should both be about 25:1.) The salt helps conduct moisture (and other flavors) into the meat, which then remains juicier when cooked. Make sure to dry them well before sauteing (and you can then skip the step of salting the surface). (2) Don't cook them for 25 minutes in the oven. I found a quick browning of 2-3 minutes on a side plus between 15 and 20 minutes in a 350 oven was plenty -- get a good digital instant-read meat thermometer, take the chops out when they're 145-150 in the center (trichonosis is killed at 137), let them rest, covered with foil, for 5 minutes before serving and they'll be great.

